Hey! 👋

I needed `isEmpty` to be fully type-safe and handle `null`, so I wrapped `remeda's` version like this (with a little help from GPT):

```ts

import { isEmpty as REmpty } from "remeda";

type IterableContainer<T = unknown> = ReadonlyArray<T> | readonly [];

// Overload: string | undefined | null
export function isEmpty<T extends string | undefined | null>(
    value: T,
): value is
    | ("" extends T ? "" : never)
    | (undefined extends T ? undefined : never)
    | (null extends T ? null : never);

// Overload: iterable containers (like array)
export function isEmpty(
    value: IterableContainer | undefined | null,
): value is [] | undefined | null;

// Overload: plain object
export function isEmpty<T extends object>(
    value: T | undefined | null,
): value is Record<keyof T, never> | undefined | null;

// Implementation
export function isEmpty(value: unknown): boolean {
    if (value === null) return true;
    return REmpty(value as any);
}

```

> but there can be unexpected cases (like human errors), that can make the input be null. In this case, it will throw a runtime error, which is unpleasant.

If a project has typing issues, it might throw in many other cases, too, not just when using Remeda utilities; that is not something Remeda is designed to address. Remeda is a **TypeScript** utility library that assumes the types in the project are sound.

e.g. 

```ts
// @ts-expect-error
const x: string = null;

// This would throw, it has nothing to do with Remeda
x.toLowerCase();
```

Remeda is not a replacement for a runtime type-validation library like https://zod.dev/, which could be used to improve the confidence that the types in your project are accurate.

