> We could also look for other parts in the code, that use `!isOnline()` and check if it should be changed to `isOffline()`, so that offline-mode works more reliably

Good idea. However, if you look at all this in General keep in mind that we also have also such scenarios on purpose:
```
context.requireOnline(purpose, false);
try {
  doSomethingWithNetwork();
} catch (IOException e) {
  if (isOfflineMode()) {
    return false;
  }
  throw e;
}
```

The idea of this pattern is that we do not have to do too many pointless online requests (flooding github.com) and prevent that if github.com would be done for whatever reason that this blocks all other network operations of IDEasy.

While I was looking through the usages of `isOnline()`, I found this method inside `GitContextImpl.java`:


```
  private void handleErrors(Path targetRepository, ProcessResult result) {
    if (!result.isSuccessful()) {
      String message = "Failed to update git repository at " + targetRepository;
      if (this.context.isOffline()) {
        this.context.warning(message);
        this.context.interaction("Continuing as we are in offline mode - results may be outdated!");
      } else {
        this.context.error(message);
        if (this.context.isOnline()) {
          this.context.error("See above error for details. If you have local changes, please stash or revert and retry.");
        } else {
          this.context.error("It seems you are offline - please ensure Internet connectivity and retry or activate offline mode (-o or --offline).");
        }
        this.context.askToContinue("Typically you should abort and fix the problem. Do you want to continue anyways?");
      }
    }
  }
```

I am a little bit confused about the functionality: in the `if` it says  `if (this.context.isOffline())` which means `if (!isOnline() || isOfflineMode())` but then in the interaction underneath, it says `"Continuing as we are in offline mode - results may be outdated!"` which does not have to be true - we could also be actually offline and not just in offline mode.

Then inside the `else` we check `if (this.context.isOnline())` and then also do an `else` here. This `else` will never be used, as inside this Block `isOnline() && !isOfflineMode()` is true.

@hohwille  Should this method be refactored?

I have just published a package [@yeliex/fastify-problem-details](https://www.npmjs.com/package/@yeliex/fastify-problem-details), which implements RFC 9457, the newer version of RFC 7807.

Itâ€™s a Fastify plugin and utility designed to handle HTTP API errors in a standardized way. The package provides:
- RFC 9457-compliant error responses: Ensures machine-readable error details in HTTP responses.
- Built-in HTTP error types: Quickly create common HTTP errors like 404, 500, etc.
- Fastify integration: Automatically handles errors and formats responses seamlessly.
- TypeScript support: Includes type definitions for better development experience.

**Example usage**:
```typescript
import Fastify from 'fastify';
import { fastifyProblemDetails } from '@yeliex/fastify-problem-details';

const app = Fastify();
app.register(fastifyProblemDetails);

app.get('/', async (request, reply) => {
    // or any other error instances
    throw new app.httpErrors.NotFound('Resource not found');
});

app.listen({ port: 3000 });
```

*Visit [readme](https://github.com/yeliex/fastify-problem-details) for more usage*

**Why not implement Problem Details directly in fastify-error**
Problem Details, as defined by RFC 9457 is standardized format for HTTP API error responses, but `fastify-error` primarily focused on error creation and management within Fastify applications.

Implementing Problem Details directly within fastify-error would introduce unnecessary complexity and coupling, making it less modular and harder to maintain. Instead, Problem Details is better suited as an external package, allowing developers to integrate it flexibly into their projects as another option to response errors.

